In order to understand the effect of precursors on the optical properties of the obtained CNPs, we also studied the UV–vis spectrum and photoluminescence spectra of the CNPs prepared using silk solution (Fig. 5
                        ). When compared with the CNPs prepared from degummed silk, it is quite clear that the UV–vis absorption spectrum shows no difference; both have broad absorbance in the UV region with two shoulder peaks at 325nm and 275nm. However, the photoluminescence shows some difference. Unlike the CNPs prepared by degummed silk, CNPs prepared by silk solution exhibits no emission peak with excitation wavelength less than 350nm. And the strongest emission peak is at 507nm with excitation wavelength of 450nm (Fig. 5A). Furthermore, the emission peaks from CNPs prepared by silk solution show red shift with the same excitation wavelength, as is summarized in Table 1
                        .
